3:41 p.m.  Defendant Todd N. Triebold in court with attorney Jeremiah James Harrelson.  Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court addresses Froelich regarding PSI. Froelich agrees with PSI.  Court addresses Harrelson regarding PSI.  Harrelson notes discrepancies in PSI.  Court notes substantive changes to be made in PSI.  Court will note changes on PSI as requested and submit to DOC.  Froelich gives sentencing argument, supports PSI given the nature of the offense.  Requests 3 years probation with recommendations as noted.  No confinement appropriate.  Harrelson - basically in agreement with Froelich's recommendation but is asking for 2 years.  Harrelson addresses pre-sentence credit.  280 days plus 245 days for a total of 525 days credit.  Defendant addresses the Court regarding sentencing.  Feels time served is suitable.  Court addresses defendant.  Froelich unsure about days of pre-sentence credit.  Froelich has 10 days to research and get back to court on pre-sentence credit.  Court orders S/W, 2 year probation, no specific conditions  of probation, defendant to comply with Wisconsin registration laws, DNA Sample, $250 surcharge, supervision fees if any, any programing recommended, no contact with minors without prior agent approval.  Appeal rights are given.  Defendant addresses court regarding transport back to Rush City, needs to go back as soon as possible.  Will do best they can to get defendant back as soon as they can through the Sheriff's Dept.  4:20 p.m.

8:40 a.m.  Defendant Todd N. Triebold in court with attorney Jeremiah James Harrelson.  Defendant Todd N. Triebold in custody.  Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Harrelson addresses the court regarding his Motion to dismiss for lack of jurisdiction and motion to dismiss on double jeopardy.  Harrelson requests dismissal on grounds indicated.  Froelich addresses the court.  Court addresses the parties regarding double jeopardy.  Harrelson addresses the court.  Froelich addresses the Court.  Court addresses the parties.  Court - will start trial, take testimony and court will consider double jeopardy issue before making a ruling.  Attorneys research interstate detainer statutes.   Detainer received April 4, 2017.  September 29, 2017 would be 180 day time limit.  Court - Will go forward with testimony and court will make decision on double jeopardy issue and jurisdiction before reaching a verdict.  Froelich - no opening statement.  Harrelson gives brief opening statement.  Froelich calls Sarah Aho.  Aho is sworn and takes the witness stand.  Froelich examines Aho. Harrelson x-exams Aho.  Court examines Aho.  Froelich redirect.  Harrelson re-x exams.  Froelich - follow up.  Froelich - Exh. #1 - confirmation letter.  Offered.  Harrelson supplements page to Exh. #1.  Redact SS#.   Off/Rec.  Confidential information to be redacted.  DL#, SS# and mother's name.  Atty Harrelson redacted requested info.  Supplement attached to Exh. #1.   Harrelson - follow up.  Froelich - follow up.  Court recesses at 9:55 a.m.  Court resumes at 10:14 a.m.  Froelich calls Officer Patrick Daly.  Daly is sworn and takes the stand  Froelich examines Daly.  Daly identifies Defendant.  Harrelson x-exams Daly.  Court excuses Officer Daly.  State rests.  Harrelson makes motion to dismiss based on  insufficiency of state's evidence.  Court reserves ruling on motion to dismiss until close of evidence.  Off record at 10:20 a.m.  Back on the record at 10:26 a.m.  Defendant will not give testimony in his own defense.   Court gives colloquy on defendants right to testify.  Defendant understands his rights and waives his right to testify.  Court approves waiver.  Harrelson requests court take judicial notice that JOC does not include judicial order to register.  Court - document will speak for itself.  Froelich has no objection.  Court takes judicial notice of Judgment of Conviction.  Defense rests.   Froelich to have written response to Harrelson's motion by September 25, 2017.  See JA for date for oral ruling on September 27, 2017.  Froelich gives closing argument.  Harrelson gives closing argument.  Harrelsont moves the court to dismiss the case today based on the insufficiency of evidence and double jeopardy.  Frolich gives rebuttal.  11:21 p.m.

The court approves the waiver of the jury trial and finds that the waiver was freely, knowingly, and voluntarily made. This case will go to the court tomorrow for a court trial.
